<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-545-664  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 545 664.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  August 14 1989 v10 n32 p26(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Solitons are the &quot;perfect wave&quot; for all-optical fiber networks.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Coursey, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>AT andamp; T Bell Laboratories researcher Linn Mollenauer is one of ateam working with perfect waves of light called solitons.andP;  Theteam is attempting to build an all-optical-fiber transmissionsystem with solitons, because they do not spread as they traveldown the fiber.andP;  Normally, pulses of light on traditionalfiber-optic networks disperse as they travel long distances.andP;  Asthe pulsating light melts into a solid beam, the information beingcarried is lost.andP;  Current fiber-optic signals have to beregenerated every 40 to 60 miles to prevent this from happening.andO;The use of solitons, which hold their shape over long distances,eliminates the need for regenerators, but 'pump lasers' are neededto keep the soliton signal from eventually fading out.andP;  The pumplasers, however, are considerably simpler and cheaper than theregenerators.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   AT and T Bell Laboratories Inc. (research).andO;Topic:     Optical CommunicationsFiber OpticsResearch and DevelopmentNetworks.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>